ssued, under the title of \u201cThe Detroit\nClub Woman.\u201d It is gotten up on a\nmagazine form and is replete witli in\nformation useful to all club women.\n\nThe Polish citizens of Detroit wili\u00ab\nbold a yiusic al and literary entettain\nineni in Poionia hall. Sunday evening,\nDec. 18. when Prof. It. Ptatkowski,\nChicago, will be the principal speak\ner. The program will be given entire\nly by Poles.\nMrs. J. P. McMahon, of Salt Lake\nCity, president of the Utah Federation\nof W mien's clubs, was the guest of j\nhonor at a luncheon held at noon, in\nthe Elllott-Tavlor-Wnolfenden Co.\u2019s\nrafe, under the auspices of the Col\nlege Equal Suffrage league.\n\nBryant Walker, a couchologist of\nwide reputation, will address the I)e\n--:rolt Mycological club, in the Scripps\nlibrary, Thursday evening, Dec. 15, on\nHaunts, home, habits and life his\ntory of fresh water clams.\u201d Although\nthe talk is under the auspices of thei\n\u2022lub members. It is open to the pub\nlic and visitors will be welcome.\n\nThe Indies\u2019 Aid society of the High\nland Park Congregational church will\n<ive a Christmas bazaar and supper,\nTuesday and Wednesday afternoon I\nind evening. Gift buyers will find J\nnuch to interest them in the many at- i\nractive novelties to be placed on sab.\nSupper will be served Tuesday eve\nling, from 5 to 8 o'clock.\n\nAmerican Eagle lodge, No. 441. I.\nO. F. elected the following officers\nor the ensuing year. Friday: Noble j\ngrand, Thomas Reid; vice-grand, F. C.\nJchurstine; recording secretary, J. B j\niouck; financial secretary, t). M.\nCox. treasurer, F. J. Herns; trustees,\nJeorge 1,. Carman and William Good\n\u2022eaj-.\nThe Joint Masonic association, com\njosed of all of the Masonic lodges 91\nDetroit, will give an afternoon reeep\nion, turkey dinner and dancing party,\ns'ew Year\u2019s day, in the Masonic tem\n>le. The executive committee of the\nissociatiou, composed of Edward H.\nSmith, Dr. Frederick H. Newberry and\n)r. Claude W. Moore, will have the\nictive co-operation of the following\nepresentatlves from the different\nodges making up the association: De\nrolt, George Straw; Union, Theodore\nSmith; Ashlar, George A. Jacobs;\nJriental, Charles T. Kingston; Corin\nhlan, Del A. Freeland; Schiller, Leo\nTaube; Friendship. Ocorge H Phil\nips; City of Straits, Francis A. Hil\non.\n\u20144^\u2014\nJacques Margoiis. the young violin-\nBt, in whom a number of Detroitei\u00df\n,re interested and who Is now studv\nng in Brussels as the result of the\n(Torts of hie Detroit patrons, has gob\nen along so well in his studies that\nits teacher has entered him as a com\nletltor for the first prize in a public\nixamlnatiois held yearly In the Brus\nels Conservatoire, Jacques to cotn\nete In 1913. Only the very best pu\nills are permitted to enter the coin\nletltton.\n**l knew you would be here this eve\nlng.\u201d said little brother,\n\u201cIntuition?\" asked the big sister\u2019s\nallow.\n\"No. observation. You always come\nn the evening Sis refuses onions\ninner.\"\nSaved From Awful Death.\nHow an appalling calamity in his\namlly was prevented Is told by A. D.\nMcDonald, of Fayetteville. N. C., R F\nNo. 8. \u201cMy sister had consump\nion,\u201d he writes, \u201cshe was very thin\n,nd pale, had no appetite and seemed\no grow weaker every day, as all\nemedies failed, till Dr. King\u2019s New\nMscovery was tried, and so complete\ns cured her, that she has not been\nroubled with cough since. Its the\ntest medicine I ever saw or heard of.\u2019\u2019\n\\>r coughs, colds, lagrlppe. asthma,\nroup, hemorrhage, all bronchial trou\nlea, It has no equal. Guaranteed by\nC. Klnsel, Central Drug Cos., Gray\nt Worcester.\nA Holiday InKSrallon.\nAmong the. many u***ful urtlclcy ap\nroprlatc for a Chrlatm&a gift, a good\nt>v r.taln pen la perhaps wait In the\nsad In selecting crtlela of this\natura, hewever, it la Important to\n\u2022l\u00abct one of known quality and repu-\nMlon. Detroit people Hie particularly\nortunate In having as one of their\nrtnctpal Industries the moat oxten-\nIvelv id favorably known fountain\nen made. The \u201cLaughlin,\" and simp\ners. especially those not familiar with\nhe various makes, should see to It\nfiat in selecting a fountain pen for\nfriend that they secure one with a\n\u2022putntlon for high class Look for the\name ''Laughlin stamped upon the\niiulne article, and do not he misled\ny v-heap Imitations.\nIn case the pen yctu select for a friend\nhould prove too tine oi too coarse; too\nard or too soft: too iar\u00abe or too\nmall. If It is a Laughlin It may be\nhanged at one of the retail stores of\nHa company, until the owner is suited,\nistaad of being obliged to send It to\nMissouri'' as is the case with out-of*\n>wn makes j\nNatural History Stories\nTold For Our Boys And Girls\nTHE CROCODILE.\nI\nf.stives are warned of the stealthy\napproach of the crocodile by the\npungent odor of niusk which that ani\nmals emits at all times. Crocodiles\nare often killed with an iron barb\ntipped Javelin and sometimes with a\nbullet which, notwithstanding tradi\ntion. easily pierces his armored hide.\nThe natives eat the crocodile flesh,\nuse the fat. regard the eggs as deli\ncacies anil prize the nnisk glands high\nly, using the musk as ointment for\ntheir hair and body.\nCrocodiles inhabit many parts of the\nglobe. They ore quite common in the\nsouthern part of pur own country, es\npecially in Florida, where It is sup\nposed they lay In wait on the river\nbanks, to swallow alive some 'unfor\ntunate pickaninny. That, however, is.\nnothing more nor less than the most\noutrageous nature faking. While it is\ntrue that crocodiles frequently kill\nhuman beings for food, there Is no\ntruth in the swallowing alive fiction.\nDespite the crocodile\u2019s enormous\nmouth, its throat Is small. This ugly\nreptile finds It necessary to take small\npieces of food at one time, because of\nits rigidly articulated jaw, and un\nelastic throat. All its large prey must\nfirst be torn into little bits before Mr\nor Mrs. Crocodile can make a meal of j\nit. WJum the crocodile is angry he\nlives to a good old mgo\nand often passes the century mark.\n4n old countries during the winter and\nin warm climates In times of drought\nthe crocodiles bury themselves in the\nmud from which they emerge upon\nthe return of prosperity. These rep\ntiles are tricky and have the advun\nS A\u2019 Panorama of Dainty Chfoa\nH \u201ef Pin Effjlpllpgg In the Crowley-Milner Basement I Beautiful Assortment. ter Plat s, 25c.\nHolder*. Others, 10c to 980\n50c. Other* It Has Been Estimated By Our China Expert, Who Ought to Know, 9\nfrom 25c Bon Bon Dishes. 75c. da I\n*iJL That \u2014More Than Ten Thousand\nPieces of China Are Here J\nJSHL. From Ever y Country On the Globe\nOh JPiL n 50c \u00abo\u00b09u. r Where China-Making Is An Art er\nIt would be strange, would it not, if nothing could be found to give that\nChina-loving friend of yours in such a vast collection as this?\nw\u00ae\\| Tr.'jT, Prices Are the Lowest in Every Instance\no.h,!T\u00bb\u00abml2i^\u00bbi. S a No One Rivals Us in China-Prices Wmlm wK/JT*\nj H l MUCH j\nCrtarn otter *t. $9 's\u2019o. 0\n75c. Othrr* up Rudolstodt, Vases, $1.98. Chop Plates, 98c. Japanese Hand-painted Salad Rudo *todt\nto $1.98. Others up to $5.98. Others 50c to $5.00. BowK, $1.37. p Others up to\nThe Christmas Store\nWith the Little Prices\nTHE DETROIT TIMES* TUESDAY. DECEMBER 13, i 9 i\u00ab.\ntage of being equally at homo on land\nand In the water. They often use\ntheir compressed, powerful tails as\nweapons with which they sweep their\nunsuspecting prey Into file water ami\nhold them until they are drowned.\nThe ancient Egyptians used to wor\ni ship the crocodiles of the Nile and\nwhen these ugly reptiles died they\n1 were embalmed. The monster croco\n-1 diles are now extinct and tbe fossil\nancestors of the crocodile of today,\nespecially the one known as the genus\nrhamposuchus of the Siwalik Hills of\n1 India, attained n length of over 50\nIcet.\nI The crocodile usually leads a peace\ni fill, domestic existence, but when hun\ngry and no other food is to be had\nlie turns Into a cannibal and eats Ills\nown batiles.\nWhile the alligator is of the eroco\ndile family, It differs from (he croco\ndile in a lew respects. The feet are\nless webbed, and the head is shorter\ni and flatter and In* is less aquatic. The\nhunters who are after the valuable\nskin, killed In the United States be\ntween lkku and 1800 3,000,000 of these\nreptiles. Alligators are of slow\u2019\ngrowth. At tile age'of 15 they are\nonly two feet long and if you ever see\na 12-foot alligator splashing around\nin a zoo tank you can make up your\nmind that hu age is about seventy-five\nand if he\u2019s longer thun 12 feet he may\nlie a centenarian.\nThe sultan of Morocco believes that\ncertain members of legtslathe bodies\nshould have their ears cut off. Con\ngress meets Monday, Dec. 5.\nCrowley, Milner (T&> Company^\nYULE TIDE bAIR T TALES XS,\nFATHER AND MOTHER AND GRANDPA AND EVERYBODY.\nNANNETTE AND THE FAIRY CROW.\nA great steel millionaire\u2014that is.\na rich man who owned many big\nfactories which made steel rails, and\ncars, und wheels\u2014lived in n mansion\nand had much money, which makes u\nmodern man ifreai. H ehad but one\nchild, a girl of eleven years, who was\npretty enough and sweet enough, bin\nwho was very, very stupid.\nHer Pittsburg parents called her\nNannette because they had traveled\nin France. Onoe blio heard her fath\ner and mother say how stupid sue\nway, so it made her sad and she wan\ndered about alone continually, often\nrefusing to even allow her uurse to\ngo with her. which they thought an\nother proof of her stupidity.\nOne morning she w\u2019as walking in\nthe beautiful woods near home when\nshe heard her nuine\u2014\u201cNannette,\nNannette\u201d \u2014again and again\nThe little girl stopped under a\ngreat oak tree to listen.\nI am Nannette \u2014the stupid, she\nmournfully replied.\n\u201cAnd I am Split-Tongue, the Talk\ning Crow,\u201d said a hoarse voice.\nNannette looked abuot her in w\u2019on\nder. She could see neither crow, nor\nman. nor woman, nor ehild nor any\nthing that resembled n fairy.\n(Nannette believed firmly in fairies\nwhich made her hard-headed father\nsure that his child was stupid. But\nwe know people who believe in fair\nies are brightest of all.)\nSuddenly a very black crow flew\ntoward her, with a rustle and perch\ned on her left shoulder.\n\u201cMy dear, you are not stupid.\u201d said\nthe talking crow.\n\u201cWhy, you can talk replied as\ntonished Nannette.\n\u201cYes.\u201d said the crow\u2019.\n\u201cAnd you are a crow,\u201d exclaimed\nNannette.\n\u201cWhich proves that you are not 30\nstupid as some people think,\u201d argued\nthe crow, \u201cor you would not be sur\nprised.\"\nNanette's eyes began to shine with\nintelligence. Already she was anew\nNannette.\nThe crow hopped to the ground,\nutiti Nannette saw a red-headed\nhunchbacked boy appear In the\ncrow\u2019s place.\n\u201cWhy\u2014why!\u201d cried Nannette.\n\u201cHow 1 shall love to play with\nyou,\" Nannette said. \u201cBut,\u201d and sho\nlooked sorry. \u201cI should like you so\nmuch better \u2014if\u2014\u201d\nNannette grew very mysterious, for\nshe had a woman\u2019s soul.\nAnd the dwarf hunch hack fairy Im\nmediately turned into the most beau\ntiful straight-limbed boy of fifteen\nthat little Nannette had ever seen!\n\"Os course,\u2019*' cried the girl child,\nstanding with her hands behind her,\n\u201cyou can be beautiful, if you can\nmake me wise.\u201d\nPlacing a hand on Xannette\u2019a\nshoulder the liandsoim* boy kissed\nher on the forehead.\n\"We snail be playmates forever,\"\nhe said\nAnd the child who had been stupid,\nbut who now understood many things,\nw \u2014yjjs\ni\nr//*t I\nlearned In a few minutes, replied.\nJoyfully:\n\u201cAdonis, you are wonderful! We\nshall be playmates. Come home with\nme. I shall tell my father; and he\nshall learn about things about which\nhe has never, never even heard\nAnd they started hand In hand to\nward the great mansion.\nLOW ROUND TRIP HOME SEEKERS\u2019 RATES TO FLORIDA\nMt M Pensacola and return $32.60\nTallahassee and return 33.80\nMichigan Cira-r\u2014EE E\nGainesville and return 35.76\nOates of Sale, Om. 20, Jan. 3 and 17,Feb. 7 and2l, Mar. 7 and 21 re,urn \u00a32\nFull particulars at City Ticket Office, Detroit Opera House Block, West Palm Beach and return. 42.8 C\nand Station foot of Third St., or by writing. JOS. S. HALL, Asst. Gen. Pass. Agent, Detroit.\nV\ntor the convenience and\ninformation of members of\nAll Hives in Detroit \u00bbjj Wayne Cos.\nHeadquarters for the\nl. o. T. M. M.\nhave been established in the office of Michigan Tent,\nJones Building, 242 Griswold St\nTelephone, Main 1478-R,\nUnder the personal direction of\nMRS. MARY E. TIMMONY, member of Great Execu\ntive Committee, and\nMRS. CARRIE GILBERT, Great Hive Auditor.\n9t012a. m M Ito 5 and 7:30 to 9:30 p. m.\nMembers will kindly bring old certificates.\nSUSPENDED MEMBERS ESPECIALLY INVITED\nTO CALL.\nFull information concerning Hive Cash Prize Contest\nwill be given to each member.\nChristmas and New Year Holiday\nRates to All Canadian Points\nFast of Detroit and Fort Arthur\nOne way lowest Itret-rlana fare for the round trip. Going\nDec 24, 26. 26; return limit Dec. 27 Also Dec. 31. Jan 1 2\nreturn limit Jan. 3. 1911.\nOne way lowest tlraf-clasM (are anil one-third fur Ike\nround trip. Going Dec. 21 to Jan 2. return limit Jan. 4, 1911\nPCANADIAN 1\n\"j\n>ote Improved Trolu Service. Leaving Detroit Union Depot. 8 a. tn. daily\nexcept Sunday, 12:10 noon and 11:40 p. in daily. Ticket offices Uptown, 7\nFort-at west, and Union Depot Phorca: Alain 4884; City 442.\nA. K. KOMO.MDB, U. 1\\ A.\nI \"vwnS PdlWntxWlHMidt\nThe Christmas Store\nWith the Little Prices\nPage Five","height":"30936","width":"22071"}}
